---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import JsonLd from '../components/JsonLd.astro';
import { SITE_TITLE, SITE_DESCRIPTION, SITE_URL, AUTHOR, SOCIAL } from '../consts';

const personSchema = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'Person',
  name: AUTHOR,
  url: SITE_URL,
  description: SITE_DESCRIPTION,
  sameAs: SOCIAL.filter((s) => s.href.startsWith('http')).map((s) => s.href),
  mainEntityOfPage: { '@type': 'WebPage', '@id': `${SITE_URL}/about/` },
};
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description={`About ${SITE_TITLE} — ${SITE_DESCRIPTION}`}>
  <JsonLd slot="jsonld" data={personSchema} />

  <article class="page">
    <header class="page-header">
      <h1>About</h1>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        I'm a digital marketer by day, and an AI operator by night. I run a boutique digital
        marketing firm, and outside of that I'm spending real hours learning to build with AI, in
        public, under my real name.
      </p>

      <p>
        I'm not an engineer, and I'm not trying to become one. The bet I'm making is that the most
        useful layer to live in right now is application development: using the models and tools
        that already exist to build things that actually work. You don't need to train models or
        wire up infrastructure to ship something useful. You just need to pick up the tools.
      </p>

      <p>
        So far I've completed two Maven certifications (AI Prototyping for Product Managers; How
        to Scale a Business With Agentic Workflows), built prototypes in Replit, and designed
        multi-agent architectures to replicate end-to-end business processes. Right now I'm deep
        in the OpenClaw & Claude Code certification with AI Product Academy. The tools I'm using
        day-to-day are Claude Code, Codex, n8n, ElevenLabs, and Higgsfield. There will be more.
      </p>

      <p>
        This site is one of those projects. I built it end-to-end with Claude Code (reviewed by
        Codex along the way) as a way to learn the stack, and I'm using it as a sandbox to share
        what I'm shipping, what's working, and what isn't. The plan is simple: take everything I
        learn here and apply it back to the real-world client work I do as a marketer.
      </p>

      <h2>Elsewhere</h2>
      <ul>
        {
          SOCIAL.map((s) => (
            <li>
              <a href={s.href} rel={s.href.startsWith('http') ? 'me noopener' : undefined}>
                {s.label}
              </a>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .page {
    max-width: 40rem;
    margin: 0 auto;
    padding: 3rem 1.5rem 0;
  }
  .page-header {
    margin-bottom: 2.5rem;
  }
  .page-header h1 {
    font-family: var(--font-serif);
    font-size: clamp(2rem, 4vw, 2.5rem);
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: -0.02em;
    line-height: 1.15;
    margin: 0;
  }
</style>
